Here's how to handle all three scenarios:

### 1. Detect Current Theme & Subscribe to Changes

```csharp
// In App.xaml.cs constructor or OnStart:
AppTheme current = Application.Current!.RequestedTheme;
Debug.WriteLine($"Current theme: {current}");

Application.Current.RequestedThemeChanged += (s, e) =>
{
    Debug.WriteLine($"Theme changed to: {e.RequestedTheme}");
    // Update UI, swap ResourceDictionaries, etc.
};
```

`RequestedTheme` returns `AppTheme.Light`, `AppTheme.Dark`, or `AppTheme.Unspecified`.

### 2. Force a Specific Theme (User Override)

```csharp
// Force dark mode
Application.Current!.UserAppTheme = AppTheme.Dark;

// Force light mode
Application.Current!.UserAppTheme = AppTheme.Light;

// Reset to follow system
Application.Current!.UserAppTheme = AppTheme.Unspecified;
```

Persist the choice with `Preferences`:

```csharp
// Save
Preferences.Set("AppTheme", "Dark");

// Restore on startup
Application.Current!.UserAppTheme = Preferences.Get("AppTheme", "System") switch
{
    "Light" => AppTheme.Light,
    "Dark"  => AppTheme.Dark,
    _       => AppTheme.Unspecified
};
```

### 3. Android — Critical Pitfall

Your `MainActivity` **must** include `ConfigChanges.UiMode` or the `RequestedThemeChanged` event won't fire (Android restarts the activity instead):

```csharp
[Activity(Theme = "@style/Maui.SplashTheme",
          MainLauncher = true,
          ConfigurationChanges = ConfigChanges.ScreenSize
                               | ConfigChanges.Orientation
                               | ConfigChanges.UiMode  // ← Required!
                               | ConfigChanges.ScreenLayout
                               | ConfigChanges.SmallestScreenSize
                               | ConfigChanges.Density)]
public class MainActivity : MauiAppCompatActivity { }
```

### Quick XAML — Automatic Light/Dark Styling

For UI elements that should react without code:

```xml
<Label Text="Hello"
       TextColor="{AppThemeBinding Light=Green, Dark=Red}"
       BackgroundColor="{AppThemeBinding Light=White, Dark=Black}" />
```

This responds automatically when the system theme changes — no event subscription needed for the UI side. Use `DynamicResource` (not `StaticResource`) if you're swapping `ResourceDictionary` themes at runtime.
